  "title": "Redundancy and Single-Point Failure",
  "concept": "A system has redundancy when multiple paths can handle the same load, and has a single point of failure when losing one component stops the whole thing from working—the difference determines whether partial breakage degrades gracefully or collapses completely.",
  "interactiveId": "0a1c3f4f-b00f-4753-a8a5-b5d530264b37",
  "sourcePieceId": "2369fa71-80e3-4bab-a509-f67456c70dae",
  "publishedAt": 1779117404809,
